{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}} {{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}} [[File:Japanese chair and armrest.jpg|thumb|Traditional Japanese chair with a zabuton and a separate armrest]] A '''''zabuton''''' ({{lang|ja|座布団}}, [[Help:IPA for Japanese|[d͡za̠bɯ̟ᵝtõ̞ɴ]]]) is a Japanese [[cushion]] for sitting. The ''zabuton'' is generally used when sitting on the floor and may also be used when sitting on a chair. In a more casual setting, the ''zabuton'' can be used in conjunction with a ''[[zaisu]]'', a type of Japanese legless chair, with or without an accompanying {{nihongo|''kyousoku''|脇息}}, a Japanese-style armrest. Ordinarily, any place in Japan where seating is on the floor will be provided with ''zabuton'' for sitting comfort. A typical ''zabuton'' measures 50–70&nbsp;cm (20–30 inches) square and is several centimetres thick when new.
Zabuton are found throughout Japan and enter many aspects of the culture. *In [[Zen]] meditation, practitioners sit on ''[[zafu]]'', which is typically placed on top of a ''zabuton''. The ''zabuton'' cushions the knees and ankles. *In [[sumo]], members of the audience throw ''zabuton'' toward the ring after the upset of a ''[[Yokozuna (sumo)|yokozuna]]'' by a lower-ranked wrestler, despite the dangers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/japan/3227869/Japan-bans-cushion-throwing-at-sumo-tournament.html|title=Japan bans cushion throwing at sumo tournament|first=Julian|last=Ryall|location=Tokyo|work=The Telegraph|date=20 October 2008}}</ref> *In ''[[rakugo]]'', performers are not allowed to rise from their ''zabuton'' for the duration of their skit. *In ''[[Yose (performance)|yose]]'', notably on the long-running television show ''[[Shōten]]'', comedians receive ''zabuton'' as a form of scoring. *In ''[[jidaigeki]]'', according to a stereotype, the boss prisoner in a jail cell receives all the ''zabuton'' from his or her cell mates.
